		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Mens cuiusq[ue], is est quiq[ue].
						Sed Mens quotidiè animata; 
						et magis magisq[ue] habituata.
					</marginalia_text>
					<X-ref book_title="De re publica" language="LA" person="Cicero" text="Mens cuiusq[ue], is est quiq[ue]"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="habituata" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				"The mind is the man". 
				But the mind is daily animated, and grows more and more accustomed.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nihil planè vulgare:
						sed uel Materia, uel forma, uel aliq[u]o colore rarum,
						aut lautu[m]. Vt ne Proa[e]resius quide[m]
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Prohaeresius"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Suprà, aut Apollonius: et longè infrà,
						omnes Ciceronis, et Demosthenis: Aristotelis, et Platonis;
						Taciti, et Seneca[e] imitatores.
						Aut multò, quàm alij vlli, meliùs: aut quorsum tot studia,
						singulares
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Apollonius of Tyana"/>
					<person name="Cicero"/>
					<person name="Demosthenes"/>
					<person name="Aristotle"/>
					<person name="Plato"/>
					<person name="Tacitus"/>
					<person name="Seneca"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="quàm alij vlli, meliùs" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						obseruationes, exquisita arcana?
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Nothing is entirely common, but everything is rare or rich in either form, matter, or some color.
				Just as not even Prohaeresius above, or Apollonius; and far below are all the imitators of Cicero,
				Demosthenes, Aristotle, Plato, and Seneca.
				Either be much better than any of the others, or what is the point of all these studies, 
				singular observations, and exquisite mysteries?			
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Aut nunc, aut nunq[uam] iaciendum aureum Fortuna[e] fundamentu[m]:
						tam facultatum, quàm reputationis causa.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="nunc" type="straight"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="nunq[uam]" type="straight"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="iaciendum aurem Fortuna[e]" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Either do it now, or you will never  build the golden foundation of Fortune.
				it is the origin of both ability and reputation.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Veritatis oratio est expedita. È Senariis camerarij.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="Veritatis oratio" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The oration of truth is set free. From the [??]. <!--JG: Don't get 'senariis camerarii'-->
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
